{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"2fe613212ce085fa23b59152a6e9b233bb85cafda7ed4255bcb7dd8af6df04c4","slug":"reproducible-research.code-quality.code-quality-robust","location":"/reproducible-research/code-quality/code-quality-robust.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Writing robust code","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"The Turing Way Community","given":"The Turing Way","family":"Community"},"name":"The Turing Way Community","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true},"code":{"id":"MIT","url":"https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT","name":"MIT License","free":true,"osi":true}},"github":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way","copyright":"2019-2025","numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way/blob/main/book/website/reproducible-research/code-quality/code-quality-robust.md","thumbnail":"/error-management-1d1630a5ec914c4ad54e4d2242774c16.svg","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"code-quality-robust.md","url":"/code-quality-robust-e04bd4fbc3471ad9bbc0b8e34c5ca63a.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We all have experienced it: you just wrote a new piece of code, but when you try it, it does not work as expected.\nPerhaps there is a typo, a bug, or you just passed the wrong parameter to a function.\nIt is not a big deal, as long as you notice!\nNoticing something is wrong is the first step to fixing it.","position":{"start":{"line":4,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"key":"Zuy05hgNZ5"}],"key":"hpeGs64MvY"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Silent failures","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"IVYAKE7lTF"}],"identifier":"silent-failures","label":"Silent failures","html_id":"silent-failures","implicit":true,"key":"A3BLfazFfS"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There will be many assumptions you make when writing a program.\nFor example, the data type of your imports, the structure of a data file, but also the behavior of any dependencies, from individual functions, entire libraries, to the programming language you use and how it functions in various operating systems.\nIt is natural to have assumptions to build on.\nHowever, it can become problematic when these assumptions are incorrect for a specific instance and the program carries on regardless.\nThis is what is called a ‘silent failure’.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"K6xS4ud2w2"}],"key":"NkHVleTE8f"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Silent failures can lead to problems down the line, likely resulting in strange and unintelligible error messages that do not have anything to do with the actual problem.\nA silent failure that stays silent will generate results that are wrong, and needs sharp eyes to be detected.\nTo make sure these things do not happen, your program needs built-in checks and balances.\nHaving good error management practices dramatically reduces the chance that a problem occurs, and especially, that it passes unnoticed.\nThis chapter’s main purpose is to help you make your code robust, and capable of dealing with different potential problems.","position":{"start":{"line":16,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"key":"YGwmFNvN7l"}],"key":"cANJPKGpOg"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Workflow","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"PeA4mcEHmG"}],"label":"rr-code-error-workflow","identifier":"rr-code-error-workflow","html_id":"rr-code-error-workflow","key":"xpODHQLodk"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Step 1: Describe your assumptions","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"MC674Z2e5k"}],"label":"rr-code-error-workflow-step1","identifier":"rr-code-error-workflow-step1","html_id":"rr-code-error-workflow-step1","key":"aCDMJSsJok"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Your code contains many assumptions.\nFor example, a function performing a simple mathematical operation assumes that its input is numerical.\nWhat happens if this function is used on a bit of text?\nOr a dataframe?\nOr an open file?","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"key":"vLgdc1b6yD"}],"key":"nIpUjFVS2y"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In a different example, let’s imagine a data science workflow.\nAs part of this workflow, a column labeled “Age” is selected.\nWhat happens if this column does not exist?\nThe workflow plots the column “Age”, but the plot is cut off at age 100.\nWhat happens if the data contains ages over 100?\nOr if this column contains negative numbers?","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"key":"jKJJNaziXL"}],"key":"DuLCxOBOGr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In making decisions about cases like these, the first step is to be explicit about the assumptions made.\nTo identify assumptions in your code, you can ask yourself:","position":{"start":{"line":41,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"key":"SvmC7lerZq"}],"key":"fsfQ6tfC1C"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What type of object/data do I expect here?","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"key":"Y7Kba0riQQ"}],"key":"rmrg4lZJep"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What files need to exist for my workflow to run, and where?","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"qPQyUDit58"}],"key":"KFNPb4tA2S"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When calling a function, am I relying on default settings for arguments?","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"Qg5S1vp6cf"}],"key":"A7ptYnpE4q"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":48,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When a function returns multiple outputs, do I ensure they are in the right order?","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"kU6keiWkjk"}],"key":"T7Ve3J5O4E"}],"key":"gtCWHQBUfh"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you think critically, there is no end to the assumptions that you make.\nFor instance, you assume that a built-in function you use works in a specific way.\nLabeling all these assumptions would perhaps keep you busy eternally, and that is not the point of this exercise.\nInstead, try to focus on assumptions you make about the data and/or files a user puts into your workflow or code.","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"YuNsBOJgVa"}],"key":"n5YqY2Po1M"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Step 2: Assert/verify assumptions","position":{"start":{"line":55,"column":1},"end":{"line":55,"column":1}},"key":"GsrIk2i7o0"}],"label":"rr-code-error-workflow-step2","identifier":"rr-code-error-workflow-step2","html_id":"rr-code-error-workflow-step2","key":"ka86KJiNyK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":60,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Once you have identified assumptions, you can verify if they are true.\nThis is also called ‘","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"rd6rE6Ywd5"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"asserting","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"d9Lr3XqMsG"}],"key":"bel8P90LnA"},{"type":"text","value":"’.\nDepending on your programming language, and the nature of the assumption, there are many creative ways to do this.\nA good starting point for verifying an assumption can be an if/else statement:","position":{"start":{"line":57,"column":1},"end":{"line":57,"column":1}},"key":"tvOml35p9k"}],"key":"u7DqtngwoB"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"if my_assumption is not TRUE:\n    do something\nelse:\n    continue","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1},"end":{"line":67,"column":1}},"key":"gPuinrqCGZ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If the assumption is ","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"key":"ZF3YZaxRpd"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"TRUE","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"key":"ZnYJDixgAY"},{"type":"text","value":", nothing happens and your code executes as usual.","position":{"start":{"line":69,"column":1},"end":{"line":69,"column":1}},"key":"rU45IMjiEy"}],"key":"h0xpUBwNWn"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":71,"column":1},"end":{"line":73,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"However, simply the existence of this if/else block will be able to alert a user if an important condition is not met.\nIf they are trying to select a column that does not exist, for instance.\nOr if they are performing mathematical operations on pieces of text.","position":{"start":{"line":71,"column":1},"end":{"line":71,"column":1}},"key":"J70nr9a4Kq"}],"key":"SMkkF93v4o"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can also take advantage of errors that are raised by the programming language you use.\nWe will go into that in more detail in ","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"wjir30cx9a"},{"type":"crossReference","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Error handling","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"oOUtEfpZ5x"}],"identifier":"rr-code-error-handling","label":"rr-code-error-handling","kind":"heading","template":"{name}","resolved":true,"html_id":"rr-code-error-handling","key":"d25hVbzhDP"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"aLWMYrvNBD"}],"key":"vjdYhgMLki"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":79,"column":1},"end":{"line":79,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Step 3: Deal with unmet assumptions","position":{"start":{"line":79,"column":1},"end":{"line":79,"column":1}},"key":"xj6U9LvK8M"}],"label":"rr-code-error-workflow-step3","identifier":"rr-code-error-workflow-step3","html_id":"rr-code-error-workflow-step3","key":"lFhjWhknwA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":81,"column":1},"end":{"line":81,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What can you do when a condition is not met?","position":{"start":{"line":81,"column":1},"end":{"line":81,"column":1}},"key":"YzboiuzS1i"}],"key":"PUohbKjDlw"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":83,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are roughly three ways you can deal with an unmet assumption:","position":{"start":{"line":83,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"key":"bcWUcLq3qS"}],"key":"n2rGUoGXDi"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":85,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":85,"column":1},"end":{"line":85,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Redirect: you can send the program in a different direction based on the information you are given;","position":{"start":{"line":85,"column":1},"end":{"line":85,"column":1}},"key":"iTKkBTXOIg"}],"key":"xJO49NtZGg"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Report: you can inform the user that something is different than what the program expects;","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"pmyuy5Gn4O"}],"key":"X7FNVwmeLQ"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":87,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Abort: you can stop executing the program.","position":{"start":{"line":87,"column":1},"end":{"line":87,"column":1}},"key":"NR2sqaNmKq"}],"key":"blMrfnutzz"}],"key":"jDbNUdcIOe"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":93,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"All programming languages have the option to raise an error.\nThese errors can come in different flavors.\nTwo main flavors that you will find in most programming languages are ‘warning’ and ‘error’.\nA ‘","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"xKRypgigWP"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"warning","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"oJzrFMJF8K"}],"key":"K5q1J6S3Vg"},{"type":"text","value":"’ is less severe than an ‘error’; it indicates a potential problem, but does not stop the program.\nAn ‘","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"Je1cf8P77b"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"error","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"CPCIKd5enG"}],"key":"M5NDm0amkj"},{"type":"text","value":"’ is thrown when the program needs to halt.","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"xhde3wYeQ8"}],"key":"TxTrzcQRwK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Thus, error types fit well with the different ways of dealing with unmet assumptions:","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"key":"H4fqK3xexc"}],"key":"aSrUf503Rm"},{"type":"table","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"tableRow","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"tableCell","header":true,"align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"children":[],"key":"uIlG1fYgG6"},{"type":"tableCell","header":true,"align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Error type","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"key":"AhYWfdO808"}],"key":"m0FuPs8zxV"},{"type":"tableCell","header":true,"align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Action","position":{"start":{"line":97,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"key":"VWZRBjC1Rq"}],"key":"FWZf9Ts7To"}],"key":"h8yVtcE08m"},{"type":"tableRow","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"tableCell","align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Redirect","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"XeCvx71jA7"}],"key":"tLixQMBOeC"},{"type":"tableCell","align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"None","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"gziQeEhONG"}],"key":"tR3Hgkbwyg"},{"type":"tableCell","align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Choose next step","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"fKSrS2exU2"}],"key":"idoTFqIA4h"}],"key":"gt0Ei6cAe9"},{"type":"tableRow","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"tableCell","align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Report","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"key":"cXxqp5Poda"}],"key":"gnwMWZs2Qr"},{"type":"tableCell","align":"left","position":{"start":{"line":100,"column":1},"end":{"line":100,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Warning","position":{"start":{"line":